Durban - A man was killed following an argument over cigarettes in Verulam. Prem Balram, the director of Reaction Unit SA,  said it was alleged the deceased and his employer, who owns a bottle store in Moss Street, were involved in an argument with a customer over the sale of cigarettes on Sunday. "During the argument, it is alleged the customer drew a knife and stabbed the deceased in the chest and his employer on his shoulder. The suspect then fled the scene on foot." Balram said when members of Reaction Unit South Africa arrived on scene the injured man who was bleeding profusely from his chest had collapsed on the pavement. "The man who was found to have sustained a single stab wound to his chest. He showed no signs of life and was declared deceased on arrival. "We conducted an extensive search for the suspects however no arrests were made." He said the employer was transported to hospital. KZN police spokesman, Colonel Thembeka Mbele, confirmed the death of the 40-year-old man. "A case of murder was opened at Verulam police station and no arrest has been made at this stage." POST  